📘 Loki + Grafana Setup Documentation (Kubernetes)

This document describes the end-to-end setup of a centralized logging system using:

Loki – Log storage

Promtail – Log collector

Grafana – Visualization & alerting

Kubernetes – Log source

1️⃣ Install Loki (Helm)
Add Helm Repository
helm repo add grafana https://grafana.github.io/helm-charts
helm repo update
Create Namespace
kubectl create namespace logging
Install Loki (Single Binary Mode)
helm install loki grafana/loki-stack \
  --namespace logging

Or install only Loki:

helm install loki grafana/loki \
  --namespace logging
Verify Pods
kubectl get pods -n logging

You should see:

loki

promtail (if using loki-stack)

2️⃣ Install Promtail

If not using loki-stack:

helm install promtail grafana/promtail \
  --namespace logging \
  --set "loki.serviceName=loki"
Verify
kubectl get pods -n logging

Promtail should be running on all nodes.

3️⃣ Verify Loki is Receiving Logs

Port forward Loki:

kubectl port-forward -n logging svc/loki 3100:3100

Test:

curl http://localhost:3100/ready

Expected output:

ready

You can also check logs:

kubectl logs -n logging deploy/promtail
4️⃣ Add Loki Data Source in Grafana

Open Grafana

Go to:
Connections → Data Sources

Click Add data source

Select Loki

URL:

http://loki.logging:3100

Click Save & Test

You should see:

✅ Data source connected successfully

5️⃣ Test in Explore

Go to Explore

Select Data Source: Loki

Run:

{namespace=~".+"}

If logs appear → Loki is working correctly.

